user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following OS_CondVarCreate code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 21.17.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.17 is Use of the string handling functions from <string.h> shall not result in accesses beyond the bounds of the objects referenced by their pointer parameters.
This rule strictly applies to the Standard Library functions in <string.h> such as memcpy, memmove, memset, memcmp, strcpy, strncpy, strcat, strncat, strlen, and strspn.
</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of OS_CondVarCreate.
```c
int32 OS_CondVarCreate(osal_id_t *var_id, const char *var_name, uint32 options)
{
    int32                         return_code;
    OS_object_token_t             token;
    OS_condvar_internal_record_t *condvar;

    /* Check parameters */
    OS_CHECK_POINTER(var_id);
    OS_CHECK_APINAME(var_name);

    /* Note - the common ObjectIdAllocate routine will lock the object type and leave it locked. */
    return_code = OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew(OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR, var_name, &token);
    if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        condvar = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_condvar_table, token);

        /* Reset the table entry and save the name */
        OS_OBJECT_INIT(token, condvar, obj_name, var_name);

        /* Now call the OS-specific implementation.  This reads info from the table. */
        return_code = OS_CondVarCreate_Impl(&token, options);

        /* Check result, finalize record, and unlock global table. */
        return_code = OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew(return_code, &token, var_id);
    }

    return return_code;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The macro uses strncpy(ref->namefield, nameval, sizeof(ref->namefield)-1). If nameval does not contain a NUL within the first sizeof(ref->namefield)-1 bytes (for example nameval points to a shorter/non‑terminated buffer, e.g. a caller-supplied char buf[8] that is not NUL-terminated while sizeof(ref->namefield) is 32), strncpy will read up to that many bytes from the source and can access memory beyond the bounds of the object referenced by nameval. Thus the use of strncpy here can result in out-of-bounds accesses unless the caller/preceding checks guarantee the source length/termination.
</scenario>
